                  "type": "paragraph"
                },
                {
                  "alignment": "center",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "styles": [
                        "bold",
                        "color:rgb(255, 255, 255)"
                      ],
                      "text": "Grand Symphony",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "level": 1,
                  "type": "heading"
                },
                {
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "alignment": "left",
                      "type": "custom_image",
                      "url": "https://act-upload.hoyoverse.com/event-ugc-hoyowiki/2024/05/19/237301566/4417194d9a22aa68cbc2c9d4aa037acd_924714980950165565.png"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "Upon return from the Primordial Sea, the glorious king established the golden imperial capital and stood astride the world as the Sebastos. Wherever his great ships sailed, all cities bowed to his supreme authority, Wherever the notes were sounded, the symphony of civilization replaced their savage songs. Ancestors of the present-day Fontanians were afraid of him and thus called him \"Dark Lord Remus.\"",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type": "paragraph"
                },
                {
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "From the moment he learned of the prophecy, Remus wondered what empire could possibly last a thousand years. He combined the immortal stone with the Ichor essence extracted from",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "granted by Egeria and gifted Remurians new eternal bodies. The Sebastos hoped that Remurians could escape the prisons of rotting flesh and fate. His great vision was that Remurians should all escape the shackles of Fortuna, becoming the masters of their own destiny.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type": "paragraph"
                },
                {
                  "alignment": "center",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "styles": [
                        "italic"
                      ],
                      "text": "\"If the waves shall devour my subjects, then I shall seal their souls in an Ichor that is utterly insoluble in all waters.\"",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type": "paragraph"
                },
                {
                  "alignment": "center",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "styles": [
                        "italic"
                      ],
                      "text": "\"If time shall rot my realm, then I shall forge imperishable bodies of bronze and stone for them.\"",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type": "paragraph"
                },
                {
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "alignment": "right",
                      "type": "custom_image",
                      "url": "https://act-upload.hoyoverse.com/event-ugc-hoyowiki/2024/05/19/237301566/6fa36af0507dcdef5030c81c7a0a8023_6753521086480853967.png"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "Remus locked himself in the depths of his imperial palace, searching for a flaw in the Master of Fortuna's music. After countless days and nights, Remus grasped the mysteries of Fortuna. He read every note of fate but lacked a \"pen\" to write down his own symphony. Thus did the Sebastos resolve to appeal to Sybilla, for she came from the land of the dead, and the torrents of fate once coursed through her veins. Remus understood that the solution lies in the people's souls that couldn't overcome the power of predestination, and thus wrote the Symphony — a music that could weave destiny. The \"Symphony\" is human memory and persona woven into a melody through musical notation, creating a song in which human souls can dwell and have their wishes fulfilled. The Golden Bee told him that to master the \"Symphony\" is to master \"fate.\" The Sebastos who created the \"Symphony\" poured these melodies into the insoluble Ichor in hopes that all might control their fates through playing that music.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type": "paragraph"
                },
                {
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "alignment": "left",
                      "type": "custom_image",
                      "url": "https://act-upload.hoyoverse.com/event-ugc-hoyowiki/2024/05/19/237301566/bb04749691763bf91c08ae162788a488_4498508554080447931.png"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "However, this did not help change the prophecy. The pain of severing soul and body cannot be endured by any ordinary life, and the God King's order tore apart and shattered souls. The Ichor was dyed black by the pain of so many souls, and it lost its harmony and wisdom, leaving only chaos and madness. People could not bear the burden of fate, and they begged their god and superiors for guidance. At their request, the Sebastos joined all the melodies to the greatest of melodies, and this would bring them the greatest happiness. The people named this symphony \"Phobos.\" Had Remus's plan worked, the Symphony would have woven a melody of utmost gentleness for them all — an eternity that would last a thousand years and beyond. In the wildest fantasies of the Sebastos, at the grand finale of the harmonious opera, he would hand fate's baton into humanity's own hands. To keep the people of the High Sea from destroying the symphony of universal harmony, King Remus promoted four humans of great capability to the high post of Harmosts to lead after him.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type": "paragraph"
                },
                {
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "alignment": "right",
                      "type": "custom_image",
                      "url": "https://act-upload.hoyoverse.com/event-ugc-hoyowiki/2024/05/19/237301566/c1f51031792713f423f4d4a2a3b55b2f_1877279809273997464.png"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "Since \"Phobos\" was the sum of all wishes and thoughts of the Remurians, it included plunder, hatred, and slaughter as part of them. Amongst the God King's sins, the most terrible was the attempt to pass power that should have been reserved for the godly domain to humans. The power and status led people to corruption and decadence, leading to violence and revolts. Even the most savage and violent of Vishaps would never engage in such meaningless slaughter. But Remus couldn't bring himself to punish the people - he loved humanity.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type": "paragraph"
                },
                {
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "When the God King realized that \"Phobos\" was leading Remuria to fall, he decided to destroy the Grand Symphony. He created his last symphony, Requiem, which was an order for the Phobos to self-destruct, and entrusted it to his friend, Scylla. According to the secret plan, Scylla was supposed to lead an army of Vishaps to assault the capital. Remus was to sacrifice himself to unleash the symphony's power, and the prince of the Vishaps had to control the primordial, savage energies that he would awaken. He hoped that he would free his subjects from their stone bodies and give them back forms of flesh and blood, destroying the artificial barrier between races. The God King separated the melody of the Harmost Cassiodor from the Grand Symphony and sent him to Ouranopolis, the city of the future.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type": "paragraph"
                },
                {
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "alignment": "left",
                      "type": "custom_image",
                      "url": "https://act-upload.hoyoverse.com/event-ugc-hoyowiki/2024/05/19/237301566/e6ded426211e34a86d94bbb81d526d43_2689578519176244197.png"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "The Sebastos's dreams didn't come true. Phobos, which absorbed one of the Remurian Harmosts, imprisoned the Dragon Prince and shut the Initium Iani leading to the capital. Scylla was unable to reach the Golden Palace in time, and Remus's sacrifice was in vain. The power of Phobos went out of control, and the empire plunged into the depths of the ocean as if submitting to heavenly punishment. On that day, Remus disappeared without a trace, and the golden civilization sank to the bottom of the sea along with its former glory. Only a thousand years later, Cassiodor finally completed the Sabastos's plan, freeing the souls of the Remurians.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type": "paragraph"
                },
                {
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "styles": [
                        "bold",
                        "color:rgb(255, 215, 128)"
                      ],
